#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:145-1
msgid ""
"When you select to create or modify an event, a series of dialogs prompts you "
"through each of the settings for the event. Select Next after choosing each "
"setting, and select Finish when you have completed all the dialogs. If you are "
"assigning multiple actions to the same type of event, after completing the "
"dialogs, <b>TAB</b> past the Finish button and select the Add Another Event "
"button. You are returned to the Actions dialog where you can assign another "
"action to the event. The Events Properties dialog lists an event for each "
"action you assign, and they are in the order you added the actions."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:146-1
msgid "For more information, refer to <a href=\"events.htm\">Frame Events</a>."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.h2:147-1
msgctxt "HTM_po_nelkul\\frame_properties.htm+html.body.h2:147-1"
msgid "Position Properties"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:148-1
msgid ""
"Use the Position page of the Frame Properties dialog box to specify exactly "
"where you want the frame. The fields in this dialog are automatically filled "
"out when you create the frame, so use these fields to tweak the exact position "
"of your frame."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:149-1
msgid "The first group of radio buttons has two choices:"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:151-1
msgid "Distance from Left Side of Window"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:152-1
msgid "Distance from Right Side of Window"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:154-1
msgid ""
"Press <b>TAB</b> to move to the Distance edit field. Specify the distance in "
"pixels (measured either from the left or right side of the window as specified "
"by the radio buttons)."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:155-1
msgid ""
"Press <b>TAB</b> to move to the Width edit field. This field specifies the "
"exact width of the frame in pixels. This field automatically updates as you "
"change the distance of the frame from the left or right side of the window."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:156-1
msgid ""
"The second group of radio buttons is similar to the first. It also contains "
"two choices:"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:158-1
msgid "Distance from Top of Window"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.ul.li:159-1
msgid "Distance from Bottom of Window"
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:161-1
msgid ""
"This group of radio buttons also has an edit field for the exact distance from "
"top or bottom, and there is an edit field to specify the height of the frame. "
"Navigate these fields in the same way as the ones discussed above."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:162-1
msgid ""
"Use the third group of radio buttons to specify whether you want the frame to "
"be relative to the window or the screen. As you switch between these two "
"choices, the choices above change to be relative to the screen or window. For "
"example, if you choose relative to screen, the choices above change to state "
"the frame’s distance from the left of the screen, instead of distance from the "
"left of the window."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:163-1
msgid ""
"We recommend you set your frames relative to the Window for most situations. "
"If you transfer frame files to another computer using a different screen "
"resolution, your frame is more likely to work if it is set relative to the "
"Window. Additionally, frames are usually designed specifically for one window; "
"therefore they should be relative to that window."
msgstr ""

#: HTM_po_nelkul%5Cframe_properties.htm%2Bhtml.body.p:164-1
msgid ""
"The Lock to DPI check box allows you to specify that a frame will only be "
"active at the DPI (Dots Per Inch) setting at which it was created."
msgstr ""

